description:
NUMBER: 20210610
SPECIES: Periodic-cicada Fungus,[1] Massospora cicadina Peck, 1879[2]
OTHER NAMES: Snow-cone Disease[1]
LOCALITY: 12104 Tulip Grove Drive, Bowie, Maryland 20715-2336 USA
LATITUDE, LONGITUDE: 38.9671, -76.7500
DATE: 10 June 2021
HOST: Pharoah Cicada, Magicicada septendecim (Linnaeus, 1758)[3]
KNOWN HOSTS: 13 and 17 year periodic cicadas, Migicicada spp.
LIFE CYCLE: Cicadas probably are infected by fungal spores as nymphs digging tunnels in soil before emergence as adults.  Spores can germinate in a year or can remain dormant 21 years and thus be available for 13, 17, and 21-year cicada emergences.  Thus having the longest life cycle of any fungus.
USE: This fungus kills and prevents reproduction by cicadas.  As with predators, their effect seems overwhelmed by sheer numbers of cicadas.
COMMENT: Part of the Brood X mass emergence (Fig. B)
IMPORTANCE: A common name for this fungus
OBSERVERS: Dr. Ernest H. Williams, Jr.[4,5,7,8] and Dr. Lucy Bunkley-Williams[4,6,7,9]
AFILIATIONS, ADDRESSES: [4]Extraordinary Professors, Potchefstroom Campus, North-West University, South Africa; Adjunct Professors, Research Field Station, Florida Gulf Coast University, 5164 Bonita Beach Road, Bonita Springs, FL 34134; [5]Dept. Marine Sciences, University of Puerto Rico (retired); [6]Dept. Biology, UPR (retired); [7]920 St. Andrews Blvd, Naples, FL 34113-8943; [8]e-mail ermest.williams1@upr.edu; cell 239-227-3645, ORCID 0000-0003-0913-3013; [9]Cell 787-467-2179, e-mail lucy.williams1@upr.edu, ORCID 0000-0003-1390-911x.
REFERENCES:
<>Williams, E. H., Jr.  and L. Bunkley-Williams. 2021. A record of a mass emergence in the North Periodical Cicada, Magicicada septendecim Linnaeus, in the Brood X outbreak. Research Quality Report, iNaturalist #79349505, 17 May (open access) [568]
<>Williams, E. H., Jr.  and L. Bunkley-Williams. 2021. A common name “Periodical-cicada Fungus” for Massospora cicadina Peck in the North Periodical Cicada, Magicicada septendecim Linnaeus, in the Brood X outbreak. Research Quality Report, iNaturalist #82885918, 13 June (open access) [569]
ADDITIONAL FOOTNOTES:
[1]Since we are not aware of a common name for this fungus and disease; therefore, we suggest “Periodical-cicada Fungus” and “Snow-cone Disease”, respectively.
[2]Identification was peer-reviewed, text edited and condensed.  The entire, original text is available in our reprint 569.
[3]Similar Species: Cassin’s 17-year Cicada, Magicicada cassinii (Fisher, 1852), differs by having all-black beneath the thorax instead of black with distinct orange bands, and orange instead of brown legs.  Decula 17-year Cicada, Magicicada septendecula Alexander and Moore, 1962, is smaller and rare.  It similarly has well-defined orange stripes on the underside of the abdomen but no orange coloration in front of the wing insertion behind the eye.  Riley’s 13-year Cicada, Magicicada tredecim (Walsh and Riley, 1868), is light orange to caramel on the underside of the thorax and abdomen.
